      <h2>How to Use the Mean Median Mode Calculator</h2>
      <p>Enter your numbers separated by commas in the text field. The calculator instantly computes the mean, median, mode, range, minimum, maximum, standard deviation, and variance. Results update in real time as you type, with no button to press or page to reload.</p>

      <p>Understanding measures of central tendency and spread is essential for anyone working with data. Students learning statistics, researchers analysing survey results, teachers grading tests, and business analysts reviewing performance metrics all benefit from quickly computing these summary statistics.</p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding the Statistics</h2>
      <p>The <strong>mean</strong> (average) adds up all values and divides by the count. It represents the balance point of the data but is heavily influenced by outliers. The <strong>median</strong> is the middle value when data is sorted; it is more robust against outliers and better represents typical values in skewed distributions.</p>

      <p>The <strong>mode</strong> is the most frequently occurring value. A dataset can be unimodal (one mode), bimodal (two modes), multimodal, or have no mode at all. The <strong>range</strong> is simply the difference between the maximum and minimum values, giving a quick sense of data spread.</p>

      <h3>Standard Deviation and Variance</h3>
      <p>The <strong>standard deviation</strong> measures how spread out values are from the mean. A low standard deviation means values cluster tightly around the mean; a high one means they are widely dispersed. The <strong>variance</strong> is the standard deviation squared. In a normal distribution, approximately 68% of data falls within one standard deviation of the mean, and 95% within two standard deviations.</p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Measure</h3>
      <p>Use the mean for symmetric data without outliers, such as test scores in a large class. Use the median for skewed data like household incomes or house prices. Use the mode for categorical data or to identify the most common value. Reporting all three gives the most complete picture of your data.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the mean?</h3>
      <p>The mean is the sum of all values divided by the count. For example, the mean of 2, 4, 6 is 4.</p>

      <h3>How do you find the median?</h3>
      <p>Sort the values and pick the middle one. For an even count, average the two middle values.</p>

      <h3>What is the mode?</h3>
      <p>The mode is the most frequently occurring value. A dataset can have no mode, one mode, or multiple modes.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between population and sample standard deviation?</h3>
      <p>Population standard deviation divides by N, while sample standard deviation divides by N&minus;1 to correct for bias when estimating from a sample.</p>

      <h3>When should you use mean vs median?</h3>
      <p>Use mean for symmetric data and median for skewed data or data with outliers.</p>

